WEBVTT

1
00:00:53.119 --> 00:00:57.579
THE WORKSHOP

2
00:02:40.093 --> 00:02:42.187
There's nothing at first.

3
00:02:48.401 --> 00:02:50.062
Take the plunge.

4
00:02:50.270 --> 00:02:52.864
You can say whatever you like.

5
00:02:58.044 --> 00:02:59.170
A murder maybe?

6
00:02:59.379 --> 00:03:01.848
A good start for a thriller.

7
00:03:02.048 --> 00:03:02.742
Bravo!

8
00:03:04.884 --> 00:03:07.216
A murder isn't always at the start.

9
00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:09.616
You're right.

10
00:03:10.356 --> 00:03:13.724
It it starts with a murder,
what happens?


11
00:03:13.926 --> 00:03:15.394
Do we witness it?

12
00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:19.626
No, it's not good to see it.

13
00:03:19.866 --> 00:03:21.960
We mustn't know who did it.

14
00:03:22.135 --> 00:03:24.263
Literature is good that way.

15
00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:26.734
You can keep things back.

16
00:03:26.939 --> 00:03:31.206
You can describe the crime
without showing the killer's face.


17
00:03:31.411 --> 00:03:32.708
Like in a movie.

18
00:03:32.912 --> 00:03:36.041
It's dark
or you see through his eyes.


19
00:03:36.916 --> 00:03:39.715
- A subjective camera.
- Right.


20
00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:41.011
What is this?

21
00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.315
Mastermind?
What are these fancy terms?


22
00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:45.958
Subjective camera?

23
00:03:46.159 --> 00:03:47.456
Who can explain?

24
00:03:48.227 --> 00:03:49.695
It's when

25
00:03:50.163 --> 00:03:53.929
the camera replaces the character.
You see what he sees.


26
00:03:54.667 --> 00:03:55.759
Thanks.

27
00:03:56.669 --> 00:03:58.637
So do we see the murder'?

28
00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:02.005
I thought...

29
00:04:02.241 --> 00:04:06.235
The corpse could be found
floating in the harbor...


30
00:04:06.446 --> 00:04:07.641
I like that.

31
00:04:07.847 --> 00:04:09.713
Not very corpse-like.

32
00:04:09.949 --> 00:04:10.745
Why not?

33
00:04:11.684 --> 00:04:13.015
He could've drowned.

34
00:04:13.252 --> 00:04:14.378
All right...

35
00:04:14.587 --> 00:04:16.578
So how do we make it clear?

36
00:04:16.789 --> 00:04:18.314
Riddled with bullets.

37
00:04:18.758 --> 00:04:21.193
A bullet-riddled corpse.

38
00:04:21.361 --> 00:04:22.988
No weapon nearby.

39
00:04:23.429 --> 00:04:26.797
It's not suicide,
so it has to be a murder.


40
00:04:27.433 --> 00:04:29.595
A round from an AK-47.

41
00:04:30.336 --> 00:04:32.134
No one suicides by AK-47.

42
00:04:32.605 --> 00:04:36.872
A Kalashnikov is a war weapon.

43
00:04:37.343 --> 00:04:38.538
It slices you in two.

44
00:04:38.778 --> 00:04:40.268
Too gory

45
00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.642
Play with your dolls!

46
00:04:42.849 --> 00:04:45.875
You see sicker stuff
on the Net or TV.

47
00:04:46.119 --> 00:04:48.611
- I don't watch.
- Come on!


48
00:04:48.821 --> 00:04:51.756
Any social network you use,

49
00:04:52.225 --> 00:04:53.090
you find it.

50
00:04:53.326 --> 00:04:55.192
The other day, a pal

51
00:04:55.395 --> 00:04:58.490
posted a video of ISIS beheading guys.

52
00:04:59.165 --> 00:05:00.530
Often there's no title.

53
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.594
Know the worst? 
I saw this video

54
00:05:03.803 --> 00:05:06.135
of two-year old kids twerking...

55
00:05:06.339 --> 00:05:08.330
- What?
- Wiggling their butts.


56
00:05:09.575 --> 00:05:10.371
It's a dance.

57
00:05:10.576 --> 00:05:12.567
There's a link with ISIS?

58
00:05:13.746 --> 00:05:16.044
Stuff like that goes viral.

59
00:05:17.183 --> 00:05:19.311
It's almost porn, that dance.

60
00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:21.647
No one makes you watch.

61
00:05:21.854 --> 00:05:22.685
Not always.

62
00:05:22.889 --> 00:05:24.015
I thought...

63
00:05:25.057 --> 00:05:28.493
the corpse could be found disfigured.

64
00:05:28.928 --> 00:05:32.125
Like someone threw acid over it.

65
00:05:32.732 --> 00:05:36.327
The forehead's run into the eyes
so you can't


66
00:05:36.536 --> 00:05:37.901
recognize the eyes.

67
00:05:38.104 --> 00:05:40.266
The cheeks have run too.

68
00:05:40.506 --> 00:05:43.498
The teeth have slipped...

69
00:05:43.709 --> 00:05:45.143
Ghost rider teeth.

70
00:05:46.679 --> 00:05:47.646
All right...

71
00:05:47.847 --> 00:05:51.374
So we have to imagine the whole story.

72
00:05:51.884 --> 00:05:54.319
It's like some US series.

73
00:05:54.587 --> 00:05:56.555
- With suspense.
- Suspense!


74
00:05:56.756 --> 00:05:59.191
We'll need a CSI team.

75
00:05:59.725 --> 00:06:01.853
That's very American.

76
00:06:02.795 --> 00:06:04.320
What's that in French?

77
00:06:04.564 --> 00:06:05.656
Pathologists.

78
00:06:05.865 --> 00:06:08.163
Pathologists? Seriously?

79
00:06:08.634 --> 00:06:11.831
I'm sick of DNA.
There's no more mystery.


80
00:06:12.905 --> 00:06:14.031
- What?
- I agree.


81
00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:17.210
- What do you suggest?
- I dunno.


82
00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:20.304
Not identifying the victim is good,

83
00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.279
but I imagined more psychology.

84
00:06:23.483 --> 00:06:25.451
Psychology?

85
00:06:25.651 --> 00:06:27.312
The lady knows big words!

86
00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:29.388
Boys aren't into that.

87
00:06:29.589 --> 00:06:32.456
We learn about the victim bit by bit...

88
00:06:32.658 --> 00:06:35.457
How do you do that?
In flashbacks?


89
00:06:35.661 --> 00:06:37.493
Yeah, flashbacks maybe.

90
00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:40.222
A guy on the docks at night...

91
00:06:40.433 --> 00:06:42.458
He's there for a reason.

92
00:06:42.668 --> 00:06:46.263
Do you mean a specific area
of the docks?


93
00:06:46.472 --> 00:06:48.270
Visualize the place.

94
00:06:48.474 --> 00:06:51.409
It'll help you to describe the scene.

95
00:06:52.478 --> 00:06:53.570
I was thinking

96
00:06:54.413 --> 00:06:55.847
of the shipyard.

97
00:06:56.015 --> 00:06:59.110
It's a monumental setting, it's great.

98
00:06:59.318 --> 00:07:00.979
It's really La Ciotat's past.

99
00:07:01.187 --> 00:07:03.713
I thought of that right away.

100
00:07:03.956 --> 00:07:07.893
We all think of it-
Not very original of you-.


101
00:07:08.961 --> 00:07:11.760
Sorry. Forgive me, Boubacar.

102
00:07:11.964 --> 00:07:13.261
Something classier

103
00:07:13.466 --> 00:07:15.798
or more modern like the marina.

104
00:07:16.002 --> 00:07:18.198
Yachts, billionaires...

105
00:07:18.437 --> 00:07:23.432
Or someplace else...
Boston, Washington, New York...


106
00:07:23.643 --> 00:07:24.906
Here isn't good'?

107
00:07:25.344 --> 00:07:29.372
Look around.
Le Mugel, the coves, nice places...


108
00:07:29.615 --> 00:07:32.414
You and your US cliches... Gangs,

109
00:07:32.618 --> 00:07:33.881
the mafia, etc.

110
00:07:34.053 --> 00:07:37.683
You write a story
to escape your shit life.


111
00:07:38.157 --> 00:07:40.626
The novel has to be set here?

112
00:07:41.127 --> 00:07:42.253
Yes.

113
00:07:42.461 --> 00:07:46.796
The idea of this workshop
is to write about your town.


114
00:07:46.999 --> 00:07:48.125
A novel is fiction,

115
00:07:48.334 --> 00:07:49.301
imagination.

116
00:07:49.502 --> 00:07:52.767
We can't write in isolation
or looking in a mirror.


117
00:07:52.972 --> 00:07:53.803
It's dumb.

118
00:07:55.641 --> 00:07:58.508
You don't have to look in a mirror.

119
00:07:58.711 --> 00:08:00.645
Use your imagination

120
00:08:00.846 --> 00:08:03.372
to make your daily life an adventure...

121
00:08:04.584 --> 00:08:06.109
What's so funny'?

122
00:08:06.886 --> 00:08:08.411
An adventure...

123
00:08:09.221 --> 00:08:11.849
Adventure isn't always a world away.

124
00:08:12.658 --> 00:08:15.593
Adventure here will be tough.

125
00:08:15.761 --> 00:08:17.627
We've only just started.

126
00:08:17.863 --> 00:08:19.388
Not in this place.

127
00:08:22.068 --> 00:08:25.504
Let's keep talking,
but I suggest you take notes.


128
00:08:26.606 --> 00:08:28.131
We write already?

129
00:08:28.374 --> 00:08:30.536
No, just take notes.

130
00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:35.711
It the conversation gives you an idea,
note it down somewhere.


131
00:08:35.915 --> 00:08:38.907
- He goes swimming!
- And you don't?


132
00:08:39.385 --> 00:08:41.877
- Towel and all...
- He wants to tan.


133
00:08:42.088 --> 00:08:43.578
You can take notes?

134
00:08:45.691 --> 00:08:48.854
She's just a teacher,
not much of a writer.


135
00:08:49.462 --> 00:08:52.454
I don't like her fancy, arrogant air.

136
00:08:52.698 --> 00:08:54.132
Pretentious, like.

137
00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.894
Her Paris accent gets to me.

138
00:08:57.570 --> 00:08:59.937
I barely understand at times.

139
00:09:00.139 --> 00:09:02.164
"I'm delighted to meet you.

140
00:09:02.408 --> 00:09:04.570
"We'll do good work here.“

141
00:09:04.777 --> 00:09:08.042
"Delighted to get a vacation
out of this.“


142
00:09:08.748 --> 00:09:11.877
They rented her a really fancy villa.

143
00:09:13.152 --> 00:09:14.517
The bus!

144
00:09:14.754 --> 00:09:16.688
Shit---
Run!


145
00:09:44.583 --> 00:09:46.017
Hey, Antoine!

146
00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:48.951
Théo, look who's here.

147
00:09:50.990 --> 00:09:52.856
- Doing OK, cuz?
- And you'?


148
00:09:53.492 --> 00:09:54.789
Got a kiss for me'?

149
00:09:55.795 --> 00:09:57.763
Stop it!

150
00:09:58.364 --> 00:10:00.196
- Where were you'?
- Swimming.


151
00:10:01.033 --> 00:10:02.728
I wanna go swimming too.

152
00:10:02.968 --> 00:10:05.096
- You do?
- I'll take you.


153
00:10:06.472 --> 00:10:08.304
- See you.
- Ciao, bro.


154
00:10:08.507 --> 00:10:10.373
- Love you, Théo.
- Say bye.


155
00:10:10.843 --> 00:10:12.208
Ciao, bro.

156
00:10:30.362 --> 00:10:31.352
Hi!

157
00:10:32.832 --> 00:10:34.129
Antoine...

158
00:10:38.137 --> 00:10:40.469
Well'? How did it go?

159
00:10:41.307 --> 00:10:42.468
Fine.

160
00:10:44.210 --> 00:10:47.077
- You'll tell me about it?
- Don't worry-.


161
00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:25.377
PROTECT

162
00:12:26.912 --> 00:12:28.437
HELP OTHERS

163
00:12:32.585 --> 00:12:33.416
PREPARE

164
00:12:36.322 --> 00:12:37.346
TO DEFEND OUR VALUES

165
00:12:38.858 --> 00:12:41.020
THE FRENCH ARMY

166
00:12:49.168 --> 00:12:50.465
Watch out, will you?

167
00:12:50.669 --> 00:12:52.364
Sorry, beauty.

168
00:12:54.807 --> 00:12:55.740
Hello.

169
00:12:57.042 --> 00:12:58.476
Where do I put it?

170
00:12:58.944 --> 00:13:00.105
Here is good.

171
00:13:04.984 --> 00:13:07.078
- Had a good evening?
- And you'?


172
00:13:07.286 --> 00:13:09.254
- I didn't sleep.
- Why?


173
00:13:09.455 --> 00:13:11.253
- I watched an action movie.
- What?


174
00:13:11.457 --> 00:13:12.720
Not your type.

175
00:13:12.892 --> 00:13:15.862
And what do you think I watch?

176
00:13:16.061 --> 00:13:17.551
Gentle movies.

177
00:13:18.564 --> 00:13:19.861
I don't know...

178
00:13:20.833 --> 00:13:22.858
- Benjamin?
- No, nothing.


179
00:13:23.068 --> 00:13:26.732
Ok, thanks.
But please put your phone away.


180
00:13:26.972 --> 00:13:28.736
Etienne, any ideas?

181
00:13:28.908 --> 00:13:31.377
Yes, but nothing really...

182
00:13:31.577 --> 00:13:32.840
It's not worth it.

183
00:13:33.045 --> 00:13:35.673
It is. We'll sort them after.

184
00:13:35.881 --> 00:13:37.906
As we mentioned the shipyard,

185
00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:41.848
why not do a
story set in the past?

186
00:13:42.054 --> 00:13:43.044
Interesting.

187
00:13:43.822 --> 00:13:46.450
Did you have a period in mind?

188
00:13:47.893 --> 00:13:49.224
I thought...

189
00:13:49.828 --> 00:13:51.523
when the yard was active.

190
00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:55.360
Just before it shut down,
when things heated up.


191
00:13:55.567 --> 00:13:58.264
Great.
The chaos, the strikes and all.


192
00:13:58.504 --> 00:14:02.202
It was wild.
They tied the manager to a crane,


193
00:14:02.408 --> 00:14:04.536
burned tollbooths...
Crazy.


194
00:14:04.743 --> 00:14:06.108
They cut the tracks

195
00:14:06.712 --> 00:14:09.238
so the riot police were brought in.

196
00:14:09.715 --> 00:14:12.377
But that was before I was born.

197
00:14:12.718 --> 00:14:14.049
I wasn't born either

198
00:14:14.453 --> 00:14:17.286
but my grandad left Algeria
to work here.


199
00:14:17.523 --> 00:14:19.389
That makes me French now.

200
00:14:19.591 --> 00:14:21.582
French? What's your name'?

201
00:14:25.297 --> 00:14:26.423
Chill, you Arabs.

202
00:14:26.632 --> 00:14:27.963
Let's focus.

203
00:14:28.968 --> 00:14:33.269
Malika's right. It doesn't have to be
a period we've known.


204
00:14:33.472 --> 00:14:36.442
Yesterday you told me the idea

205
00:14:36.642 --> 00:14:39.111
is to talk about our daily lives.

206
00:14:39.812 --> 00:14:41.439
- You said that.
- I did.


207
00:14:41.647 --> 00:14:44.241
But it can be your town's past too.

208
00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:47.044
Your family's experiences.

209
00:14:47.252 --> 00:14:48.549
We don't talk about that.

210
00:14:48.754 --> 00:14:52.622
It's there subconsciously,
you've heard about it.


211
00:14:53.058 --> 00:14:56.517
I've only been in La Ciotat five years.

212
00:14:56.729 --> 00:14:59.721
My grandad told me lots of stuff.

213
00:14:59.932 --> 00:15:03.869
There was pride
in being from La Ciotat.


214
00:15:04.636 --> 00:15:08.402
Pride in welding in the dark
and breathing asbestos?


215
00:15:08.607 --> 00:15:12.441
You saw the result?
The huge things they built'?


216
00:15:13.779 --> 00:15:16.874
I can ask my grandad to help us.

217
00:15:17.783 --> 00:15:19.410
That's interesting.

218
00:15:19.618 --> 00:15:23.248
When you write a novel,
you have to do research


219
00:15:23.789 --> 00:15:27.589
to make your fiction more real.

220
00:15:29.461 --> 00:15:31.327
You're dubious, Antoine?

221
00:15:32.931 --> 00:15:35.730
I'm not keen on
a story in the past.

222
00:15:35.934 --> 00:15:37.732
I have an idea then...

223
00:15:38.303 --> 00:15:40.294
Go on, we're listening.

224
00:15:40.506 --> 00:15:42.372
I mentioned flashbacks.

225
00:15:42.608 --> 00:15:45.077
Our story could be set today,

226
00:15:45.611 --> 00:15:49.206
but the crime's motive
could lie in the past.


227
00:15:51.050 --> 00:15:53.985
That's not bad.
What do you think?


228
00:15:54.186 --> 00:15:57.053
Also, the victim could be black.

229
00:15:57.656 --> 00:15:59.351
Or an Arab.

230
00:15:59.558 --> 00:16:01.993
- Why'?
- Why what?


231
00:16:02.194 --> 00:16:04.891
Why black or Arab?
A racist crime?


232
00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:07.565
- Maybe.
- What's the point?


233
00:16:08.133 --> 00:16:09.623
He's black or Arab.

234
00:16:09.835 --> 00:16:11.098
- That's all?
- Yes.


235
00:16:11.503 --> 00:16:16.202
Why not a white victim
and a black or Arab killer?


236
00:16:16.408 --> 00:16:19.105
- Anti-white racism?
- You said it's not racism.


237
00:16:19.344 --> 00:16:20.675
You started-.

238
00:16:20.879 --> 00:16:23.007
Calm down, both of you.

239
00:16:23.215 --> 00:16:27.345
It's good to have blacks or Arabs,
like around this table.


240
00:16:27.553 --> 00:16:28.384
What black?

241
00:16:28.587 --> 00:16:30.521
Who do you mean, ma'am?

242
00:16:30.722 --> 00:16:32.884
But we can decide later

243
00:16:33.092 --> 00:16:34.958
if it's a racist crime.

244
00:16:36.228 --> 00:16:37.718
Put a question mark.

245
00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:39.364
I'll do that.

246
00:16:39.565 --> 00:16:41.226
"Racist dimension?"

247
00:16:42.267 --> 00:16:43.962
Antoine, any ideas?

248
00:16:45.838 --> 00:16:47.499
No, not really.

249
00:16:47.706 --> 00:16:52.166
I liked Bouba's idea yesterday
of using the marina.


250
00:16:52.511 --> 00:16:54.377
We're backtracking?

251
00:16:54.746 --> 00:16:56.908
The shipyard was confirmed?

252
00:16:57.116 --> 00:17:00.142
- I thought we agreed...
- We kept saying so.


253
00:17:00.385 --> 00:17:02.410
Don't ask me in that case.

254
00:17:02.921 --> 00:17:05.117
No, go on, express yourself.

255
00:17:05.357 --> 00:17:07.792
Why are you so keen on the marina?

256
00:17:08.227 --> 00:17:09.695
It's not that...

257
00:17:10.429 --> 00:17:13.091
I think it's better for a thriller.

258
00:17:13.298 --> 00:17:15.733
Yacht-owners make good victims.

259
00:17:16.535 --> 00:17:19.163
They're rich, people envy them,

260
00:17:19.371 --> 00:17:22.341
they do all kinds of shady deals...

261
00:17:22.541 --> 00:17:24.703
It makes the town look better.

262
00:17:24.910 --> 00:17:26.571
Drugs and trafficking?

263
00:17:26.778 --> 00:17:28.906
The shipyard's dead now.

264
00:17:29.114 --> 00:17:31.139
- It's history.
- Dead and buried.


265
00:17:31.383 --> 00:17:35.820
All the same,
it's the first thing you see here.


266
00:17:35.988 --> 00:17:37.149
We know that.

267
00:17:37.389 --> 00:17:40.552
Tourists talk about it,
but it's a graveyard.


268
00:17:41.393 --> 00:17:43.691
You can even see it from here.

269
00:17:51.336 --> 00:17:55.705
Rather than get stuck
